```javascript
const xmlFile = "pecan/tests/api.sipnet.xml";
const fs = new FileSystem();
fs.readFile(xmlFile, async (err, data) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error("Error reading file:", err);
    return;
  }
  const root = XMLSerializer.parseFromString(data, "text/xml").documentElement;

  try {
    const response = await fetch(
      "http://localhost:8000/api/workflows/",
      {
        method: "POST",
        headers: {
          "Authorization": "Basic " + btoa("carya:illinois"),
          "Content-Type": "application/xml",
        },
        body: XMLSerializer.serializeToString(root),
      }
    );
    const jsonResponse = await response.json();
    console.log(jsonResponse);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Error submitting workflow:", error);
  }
});
```
Note that in this example, I am using the `XMLSerializer` to parse and serialize the XML document, and the `FS` API to read the contents of the XML file. The `FS` API is a built-in JavaScript module that provides an easy way to read and write files in the browser.

To get the body content for the API request, you can use the `body` property of the `fetch` request options object, and set it to the serialized XML document.

In the example above, I am using the `XMLSerializer` to serialize the XML document, but you could also use a library like `jsdom` to create a `Document` object and serialize it using the `serialize` method.

