To create a dynamic HTML page that meets your requirements, you'd need to use C# in a web development framework like ASP.NET Core. I'll outline the steps to create a simple web application that renders the information you want.

1. Install .NET Core SDK from https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download
2. Open the terminal or command prompt and create a new web application:

```
dotnet new webapp -o ContinentInfo
cd ContinentInfo
```
3. Open the `Pages` folder and find `Index.cshtml.cs`. This is the C# backend code for the default page. Add the following class and method to fetch the information:

```csharp
public class CountryInfo
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public string Capital { get; set; }
    public int Population { get; set; }
    public int Area { get; set; }
}

public List<CountryInfo> FetchCountryData()
{
    return new List<CountryInfo>
    {
        new CountryInfo { Name = "Italy", Capital = "Rome", Population = 60360000, Area = 301340 },
        new CountryInfo { Name = "France", Capital = "Paris", Population = 66990000, Area = 643801 },
        new CountryInfo { Name = "Germany", Capital = "Berlin", Population = 83020000, Area = 357022 },
        new CountryInfo { Name = "United Kingdom", Capital = "London", Population = 66650000, Area = 242495 }
    };
}
```

4. In the `OnGet()` method, call the `FetchCountryData()` method and store the result in a `ViewData` object:

```csharp
public void OnGet()
{
    ViewData["Countries"] = FetchCountryData();
}
```

5. Open the `Index.cshtml` file to edit the HTML frontend. We will display the required information as header and table content:

```html
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home page";
    var countries = ViewData["Countries"] as List<CountryInfo>;
}

<h1>Smallest Continent: Europe</h1>
<h2>Population: Over 700 Million</h2>
<h2>Area: 10,180,000 sq km</h2>

<table>
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Country</th>
            <th>Capital</th>
            <th>Population</th>
            <th>Land area (sq km)</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        @foreach (var country in countries)
        {
            <tr>
                <td>@country.Name</td>
                <td>@country.Capital</td>
                <td>@country.Population</td>
                <td>@country.Area</td>
            </tr>
        }
    </tbody>
</table>
```

6. To add CSS styling and hover effect, open the `wwwroot\css\site.css` file and append the following CSS:

```css
table {
    border-collapse: collapse;
    width: 100%;
}

table, th, td {
    border: 1px solid black;
}

th, td {
    padding: 15px;
    text-align: left;
}

th {
    background-color: #f2f2f2;
}

tr:hover {
    background-color: #ddd;
}
```

7. Run the application using the command `dotnet run`. Open the generated URL in your browser to see the dynamic HTML page displaying Europe's information and the table with data about Italy, France, Germany, and the United Kingdom.

