The potential problem with the following C# code is that it is not thread-safe. This means that if two threads are both calling `MyMethod` at the same time, it is possible that they will print the strings out in the wrong order.

To make the code thread-safe, we can use a lock statement to ensure that only one thread can access `MyMethod` at a time. For example:

```
public class MyClass
{
    private object lockObj = new object();
    public void MyMethod()
    {
        lock (lockObj)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Hello");
            Console.WriteLine("World");
        }
    }
}
```

This code will ensure that only one thread can be inside `MyMethod` at a time, so the strings will always be printed out in the correct order.

Here is a more detailed explanation of the potential problem with the code. The code is not thread-safe because it does not use any synchronization. This means that if two threads are both calling `MyMethod` at the same time, it is possible that they will both try to print the strings out to the console at the same time. This can lead to the strings being printed out in the wrong order.

To make the code thread-safe, we can use a lock statement to ensure that only one thread can access `MyMethod` at a time. The lock statement will create a lock object that is used to synchronize access to the `MyMethod` method. When a thread enters the `MyMethod` method, it will acquire the lock on the lock object. This will prevent any other threads from entering the `MyMethod` method until the first thread has finished. This ensures that only one thread can be inside `MyMethod` at a time, so the strings will always be printed out in the correct order.

