A socket is a connection point between two devices in a network, allowing them to communicate with each other.

To illustrate this in C++ using the `socket` library, you can write the following code:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <sys/socket.h>
#include <arpa/inet.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    int sock = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);
    if (sock < 0) {
        std::cerr << "Error creating socket" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }
    struct sockaddr_in serv_addr;
    serv_addr.sin_family = AF_INET;
    serv_addr.sin_addr.s_addr = inet_addr("127.0.0.1");
    serv_addr.sin_port = htons(1234);
    if (bind(sock, (struct sockaddr *)&serv_addr, sizeof(serv_addr)) < 0) {
        std::cerr << "Error binding socket" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }
    if (listen(sock, 1) < 0) {
        std::cerr << "Error listening on socket" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }
    while (true) {
        socklen_t client_len = sizeof(serv_addr);
        int client_sock = accept(sock, (struct sockaddr *)&serv_addr, &client_len);
        if (client_sock < 0) {
            std::cerr << "Error accepting connection" << std::endl;
            return 1;
        }
        std::cout << "Connected to client " << serv_addr.sin_port << std::endl;
        send(client_sock, "Hello, this is an example network communication!", 25, 0);
        close(client_sock);
    }
    close(sock);
    return 0;
}
```
Here, the `socket()` function creates a new socket. The `bind()` function binds the socket to an IP and port number. The `listen()` function enables the socket to listen for incoming connections. The `accept()` function accepts a new connection and returns a file descriptor for the client's socket. Finally, we use the `send()` function to send a message to the client.

The `sys/socket.h` and `arpa/inet.h` libraries are used for socket programming, while the `unistd.h` library is used to perform system-related tasks like closing sockets and printing error messages.

