Yes, it is possible to export just a useEffect hook from a React component. The useEffect hook is a built-in React hook that allows you to reactively update the component's state or perform other side effects based on certain conditions. By exporting just the useEffect hook from a component, you can reuse that hook in other components and avoid duplicating the code.

To export just the useEffect hook from a component, you can define the hook separately and then export it alongside the component. Here's an example:
```javascript
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

const UseFetchData = () => {
  const [data, setData] = React.useState([]);

  // Define the useEffect hook separately
  const fetchData = React.useEffect(() => {
    // Perform data fetching logic here
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      {data.map(item => (
        <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

// Export the useEffect hook alongside the component
export { UseFetchData, fetchData };

export default UseFetchData;
```
In this example, we define the `fetchData` hook separately and then export it alongside the `UseFetchData` component. You can then import and use the `fetchData` hook in other components as needed.

