In C#, you can create a function that compares two version strings in the format of "x.y.z" by first parsing the strings into `Version` objects and then comparing them using the `CompareTo` method. Here's an example implementation:

```csharp
using System;

class VersionComparator
{
    public static int CompareVersions(string version1, string version2)
    {
        try
        {
            Version v1 = new Version(version1);
            Version v2 = new Version(version2);

            return v1.CompareTo(v2);
        }
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Invalid version format: " + e.Message);
            return 0;
        }
    }

    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string versionA = "1.2.3";
        string versionB = "1.3.0";

        int result = CompareVersions(versionA, versionB);

        if (result < 0)
            Console.WriteLine($"{versionA} is lower than {versionB}");
        else if (result > 0)
            Console.WriteLine($"{versionA} is higher than {versionB}");
        else
            Console.WriteLine($"{versionA} is equal to {versionB}");
    }
}
```

The `CompareVersions` function takes two version strings as input and returns an integer: -1 if the first version is lower, 1 if the first version is higher, and 0 if both versions are equal. Note that this implementation uses the `System.Version` class, which automatically handles comparison between version numbers.

